<br>
You're right, the A and the I should be lengthened by using a hyphen (A-, I-), NOT by repeating the vowel (AA, II).<br>
<br>
Here's the general rule:<br>
If the word is in KATAKANA, use a hyphen to lengthen the vowel.  On the other hand, if the word is in Hiragana, use a vowel-character, not a hyphen.  So a <br>
<br>
long A sound would be A- in katakana, and AA in hiragana.<br>
long I sound would be I- in katakana, and II in hiragana.<br>
long U sound would be U- in katakana, and UU in hiragana.<br>
long E sound would be E- in katakana, and EE in hiragana.<br>
long O sound would be O- in katakana, and OU in hiragana.<br>
<br>
(notice the OU thing at the end, NOT OO.  The only exception is the word OOkii, meaning BIG, which is not spelled OUKI.)<br>
<br>
You'll see minor exceptions to these spelling rules, if you read manga (Japanese cartoon magazines).  The exceptions are for effect... like when English novelists write stuff like &quot;whaddaya mean, ah don' git the gawd-derned money ?&quot;<br>
----------<br>
By the way, heads up... the guy who typed out the sentence ending in AHO was flipping you off.  Aho is a rude Osaka slang-word for &quot;mindless jerk&quot;.<br>
Not funny...and not welcome, I'd say.<br>
<br>
----<br>
A final note:  the TI part would be spelled, in katakana, with a normal-sized TE, followed by a small I, and then a hyphen.  If it's not done this way, then the sound becomes &quot;chi-&quot;, not &quot;ti-&quot;.<br>
<br>
On word-processors in Japan, you'd get that small-sized character by typing &quot;te x i hyphen&quot;.  The &quot;X&quot; means &quot;X-tra small&quot;.  *grin*  You can use the &quot;x&quot; to get any regular character in kid-size... like yo, or yu, or any of the other characters that sometimes get written smaller than surrounding characters.<br>
<br>
